'''Albert Marrin''' (born July 24, 1936) is an American [[historian]], professor of history, and author of more than forty juvenile nonfiction books.

==Life==
He was born in New York City. He graduated from [[City College of New York]], [[Yeshiva University]], and [[Columbia University]]. He taught in the public schools [[New York City]]. He is Chairman of the history department at [[Yeshiva University]].<ref>http://yu.edu/catalog/undergrad/catalog9920_women/faculty.htm</ref><ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/?id=2uRa0GbpQEQC&pg=PA123&lpg=PA123&dq=Albert+Marrin++yeshiva#v=onepage&q=Albert%20Marrin%20%20yeshiva&f=false| title=Popular nonfiction authors for children: a biographical and thematic guide| author=Flora Wyatt| author2=Margaret Coggins| author3=Jane Hunter Imber| publisher=Libraries Unlimited| year= 1998| isbn= 978-1-56308-408-9 }}</ref>

He lives with his wife in the [[Bronx]], New York.<ref>http://www2.scholastic.com/browse/contributor.jsp?id=3809</ref>

==Awards==
* 2008 [[National Humanities Medal]]
* Carter G. Woodson Award
* Boston Globe/Horn Book Award
* Dorothy Canfield Fisher Children's Book Award
* James Madison Book Award
* Washington Post-Children's Book Guild Nonfiction Award.

